   <indicator ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Output Indicator</narrative>
    </title>
    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">1.  No of Regional Women Council members with enhanced awareness on the role of women in peace and conflict resolution in Oromia and Somali regions</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2018">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. None for a specific peace building and conflict resolution capacity
2. No Data -for the assessment documents on the role of women in peace building  
3. No COVID 19 response plan to support women</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2019-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2019-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Enhanced Capacity of 73 women leaders on peace building and conflict resolution</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. 148 women leaders from CSOs(50), Regional Councils OF Oromia, Somali and SNNPR(46) , House of Federation (10), House of Peoples Representative(35), Ministry of Peace (5) and Ministry of Women Children and Youth(2) were trained to enhance their knowledge on the role of women in conflict resolution and peace building.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. COVID -19 response plan developed and implemented to support 250 women leaders and community members; 
2. 50 women leaders from CSOs, Regional Councils OF Oromia, Somali and SNNPR, Ministry of Peace and Ministry of Women Children and Youth will be trained to enhance their knowledge on the role of women in conflict resolution and peace building during COVID pandemic and election.
3. The role of women in conflct prevention and peace building in Oromia and Somali regional states assessed and shared</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">As a result of the strategies employed by WiP project, the following results has been realized in the year 2020:- 
- An assessment report on the role of women in peace and reconciliation in Oromia and Somali Regions was produced to inform peacebuilding programming by addressing the challenges of evidence on the role of women in peace and security in those targeted regions. 
- As part of the continuing efforts to building the capacity of women for peacebuilding, consecutive trainings on Conflict Prevention, Management, and Mediation Skills were provided for 424 women in addition to the 148 women who were trained in 2019. These women were from Ministry of Women, Children and Youth, Oromia Regional State Councils local CSOs, and women peace ambassadors and traditional mediators from the 9 regional states. 
- Following the spread of COVID 19 Pandemic in Ethiopia , the project also repurposed and extended with additional 6 month from June - December 2020. The aim was to address the emerging unique challenges of women both as victims of the pandemic and as agents for change in the context of peacebuilding and conflict resolution. Accordingly, 4641 Internally Displaced People (IDPs) were reached by providing with Personal Protective Equipment (PPE). 
- As part of the efforts to promoting the role of women in peace, three consecutive media panel discussions were conducted by engaging representatives of public and religious institutions, CSOs, and media houses. The panel discussions were watched by 1191 YouTube viewers in addition to the audience reached during the transmission of the panel on the public TV called Walta. Two infographic Amharic and English video messages were also produced to back the public awareness effort on the Media. These videos promote the role of women as agents of peace by highlighting their practical role in different traditional settings in Ethiopia.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
